<HEADLINE> Kim Dae-jung Appeals for National Unity to Overcome Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, January 1 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's President-elect Kim
Dae-jung today called for national unity to overcome the current
economic crisis ailing the country.
</P>
<P>
"We are facing our biggest crisis since the Korean War. We should
unite to overcome the difficulties," Kim said in his New Year's
message to South Koreans.
</P>
<P>
Kim, who won the 15th presidential election on December 19, said
he will take the lead in pain sharing while the pain should be born
evenly and fairly by all South Koreans.
</P>
<P>
He also said he would punish those responsible for economic
mismanagement.
</P>
<P>
"Stern measures should be taken against those who have caused the
national disaster," said Kim, who will be sworn in as the president
of the country next February.
</P>
<P>
He pledged to faithfully implement an agreement reached between the
Kim Young-sam government and the International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
The nation, last December, signed the agreement with the IMF for a
rescue loan of 57 billion U.S. dollars with harsh conditions.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, South Korea has to restructure its economy,
open its financial market and cut its budget while it has to face
massive layoffs.
</P>
<P>
Although 1998 will be a tough year for the country, Kim pointed
out that the current crisis is fundamentally a financial crisis,
not a crisis of the country's entire economic system because the
nation still enjoys favorable conditions, such as stabilized
prices, high growth potential, improvements in trade balance,
high-level savings ratio.
</P>
<P>
The president-elect said he is confident that economy of his
country, the 11th largest in the world, will surely recuperate and
get out of the IMF's control within the next two years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
