<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korean Per-Capita Income Down to 9,400 U.S. Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, January 1 (Xinhua) -- The year 1997 witnessed
per-capita income in South Korean dropping to 9,400 U.S. dollars
from the previous year's 10,548 dollars, said the Ministry of
Economy and Finance Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The drop was the first since 1980 when each Korean suffered a
slide of 50 dollars due to an oil shock around the globe.
</P>
<P>
Analysts attributed the decrease to the government's economy
policies and the 40 percent devaluation of South Korean won
against dollar.
</P>
<P>
They said the nation's per-capita income will fall further this
year because of the serious financial crisis began last November.
</P>
<P>
The country's economy, the analysts added, could grind to halt
without speedy assistance from international financial
organizations and industrialized countries.
</P>
<P>
Up to today, South Korea has received only 9 billion of the
agreed rescue loans totaling 57 billion dollars from the
International Monetary Fund while its won continues to
depreciation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
