<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rwandan Vice-president Warns Hutu Extremists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Hutu extremists who are waging
a war in north-western Rwanda will not overthrow the government
by the power of arms, said Rwandan Vice-President and Minister of
Defense Paul Kagame, Rwanda News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
While addressing the population of five communes of Ruhengeri
on New Year's eve, Kagame made a stern warning to the residents
of the prefectures of Gisenyi and Ruhengeri that they should be
ready to face the consequences of the war they have been dragged
into by Hutu extremists.
</P>
<P>
"You must dissociate yourselves from criminals who are
inciting you to commit killings and destroy bridges and other
infrastructures," Kagame told the crowd.
</P>
<P>
He warned those who are causing insecurity and destroying
infrastructures to cripple and finally overthrow the government
that "it is a dream."
</P>
<P>
"I repeat it, there is no clique in this Rwanda, even if
supported by foreign countries, that will topple this government
using arms, " Kagame underscored.
</P>
<P>
For Kagame, committing atrocities of all kinds, like ambushing
vehicles and killing passengers, raiding refugee camps and
massacring women and children only because they are Tutsis, will
not affect the governmnet's programs to rebuild the shattered
nations and reconcile all Rwandans.
</P>
<P>
As for alleged killings of civilians by the government forces
put forth by residents of Gisenyi and Ruhengeri, he said that the
population is partly responsible.
</P>
<P>
Kagame admitted that there might be some indisciplined
soldiers that could abuse civilians, but those found guilty of
such acts are punished. 
</P>
</TEXT>
