<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tough Choices in Year Ahead, Says UK's Blair </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 1 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
has warned Labor MPs and the general public that 1998 will be a
year of "tough choices" and will require hard work, determination
and discipline.
</P>
<P>
In his new year message published today, Blair said that the
government must continue with welfare reform, as the present
system was "failing" the poor and the country.
</P>
<P>
He said that people in genuine need of help will get it and
that talk of taking any benefit from the most vulnerable in
society is "scaremongering".
</P>
<P>
Blair outlined other key aims as effective economic management
to ensure improved living standards for ordinary families and
improving standards in education.
</P>
<P>
He said that his government is determined to deliver its
"contract with the people", with the "New Deal" for the young and
long-term unemployed being a priority.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that government achievements in the past year
included giving extra money to the National Health Service (NHS),
cutting VAT on fuel and winning referendums on a Scottish
parliament and Welsh assembly.
</P>
<P>
The Northern Ireland peace process and the UK's presidency of
the European Union would be significant in 1998, Blair noted.
</P>
<P>
"Tough choices will come. They must be faced up to. It is then
that our resolve, our strength and our commitment will be tested.
I am confident we can meet that test and change Britain for good,"
he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
