<HEADLINE> Peer AIDS Education Scores Success in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 1 (xinhua) -- HIV/AIDS peer education and
awareness campaigns at Zimbabwe's work places could be a
complementary gateway to the control of the deadly pendemic now
killing an estimated 500 people a week, the Zimbabwe News Agency
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Experts said it is affordable, sustainable and feasible.
</P>
<P>
''With peer education there is less social distance between
the workers and the educator,'' said Michael Mbizvo, a research
officer with the Zimbabwe AIDS Prevention Project (ZAPP), a
collaborative study of the University of Zimbabwe, the National
Blood Transfusion Services (NBTS) and Britain's Stanford
University.
</P>
<P>
Of the 10 Sub-saharan African countries most affected by AIDS
in Africa, Zimbabwe ranks second after Zambia with an infection
rate of one per 1,000.
</P>
<P>
The peer program, which began in 1993, is a departure from
previous HIV/AIDS programs which often focused on defined
high-risk groups which include commercial sex workers, long
distance truck drivers and known STD (sexually-transmitted
diseases) cases, leaving out the general population.
</P>
<P>
ZAPP study carried out in Harare's factories concluded that
the work places offer access to a previously ignored economically
important population.
</P>
<P>
The study, to assess effectiveness of AIDS messages when
workers are lectured to by peer educators, also sought to
determine the impact of peer education on self reported risk
behavior, knowledge and attitudes of workers regarding HIV and
AIDS and to provide counselling services for study participants.
</P>
<P>
From 1993, ZAPP enrolled 3,392 men from 40 factories into the
research program. Of them, 2,719 were HIV negative.
</P>
<P>
The three year research period recorded a 34 percent reduction
in instances of HIV and STD infection in the factories.
conclusions were based on the number of new HIV infection among
those known to have been negative at the inception of the
project.
</P>
<P>
The study designated one peer educator for every 100 workers
to continuously supply free condoms and organize at least one
drama and two presentations by persons living with HIV/AIDS.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
