<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mixed Reactions to Moi's Expected Win in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Incumbent Kenyan President
Daniel arap Moi is taking an early lead in the country's second
multi-party elections held on Monday and Tuesday, causing mixed
reactions from various opposition groups.
</P>
<P>
Based on initial results from 145 out of 210 constituencies,
Moi headed the poll with 1,686,742 votes, followed by Democratic
Party Chairman Mwai Kibaki with 1,351,614 votes and National
Development Party leader Raila Odinga with 560,594 votes,
according to Kenya Television Network's evening news reports.
</P>
<P>
Two main opposition presidential candidates announced today
they will not accept Moi as a winner while a leading opposition
lobby group, the National Convention Executive Council (NCEC),
said the poll "must be declared null and void."
</P>
<P>
At this point, a senior officer with the Electoral Commission
told Xinhua that he personally believed the opposition would
finally accept the official polling results which he said is much
likely to come out on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Kibaki and Odinga, who now take the second and third place in
early results respectively, announced today they will reject a
continuous Moi regime.
</P>
<P>
"This is a fraudulent process, so how can we accept a result
that shows Moi winning?" Kibaki said when answering questions at
a news conference held jointly held by himself and Odinga.
</P>
<P>
"We will not accept a victory for Moi because there is no way
he could have won," Odinga added.
</P>
<P>
However, they failed to reveal their further plans, if they
had any, in case of a Moi victory.
</P>
<P>
Instead, they predicted a joint opposition victory despite all
chaos and confusions occurring in the voting, saying they "are
committed to forming a government of national unity in which all
stake holders are adequately represented".
</P>
<P>
Later, NCEC spokesman Kivutha Kibwana claimed in a statement
that the poll must be annulled because it "is irreparably
manipulated" and "does not reflect the will of the Kenyan
people."
</P>
<P>
The NCEC demanded a government of national unity comprising of
parliamentarians from the just-dissolved parliament, deputies of
NCEC and the religious sector "be instituted by January 9, 1998,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the U.S. administration on Wednesday said despite
"bureaucratic flaws" in the polling process, "the Kenyan people
through their actions have demonstrated a powerful commitment to
democracy."
</P>
<P>
"We are encouraged by the level of peaceful, popular
participation in the election" in Kenya, U.S. State Department
Deputy Spokesman James Foley was quoted by reports reaching here
as saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
