<DOCNO> XIE19980102.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ugandan Officials to Declare Assets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan officials must declare
their assets and those of their spouses and children starting
from this year, President Yoweri Museveni has said.
</P>
<P>
In his new year speech to the nation broadcast by Radio Uganda
today, the president said officials must also declare the way
through which they get the wealth.
</P>
<P>
All the declarations will be made public to prevent
corruption, according to an amendment to the leadership code
newly approved by the cabinet, Museveni added.
</P>
<P>
No corruptive officials will be allowed to use state organs to
defend his corruption, the president assured the public, adding
that his government commends the efforts made by parliament and
the press to expose corruption in public services.
</P>
<P>
Museveni appealed to the public not to give bribes to
officials, and to report any official asking for a bribe.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the economic performance of the country in 1997,
the president put the rate of growth at five percent, lower than
1996's 8.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
Inflation has been kept at 6.6 percent, while foreign exchange
inflows has continued to grow to 1.8 billion U.S. dollars, of
which 653 million was from export earnings and the rest from
private inflows.
</P>
<P>
Museveni attributed the lower economic growth rate to the
erratic state of the agricultural sector caused by the temporary
drought earlier last year.
</P>
<P>
The industrial sector, however, registered a satisfactory
growth of 16 percent. The construction sector grew by 13 percent.
</P>
<P>
Museveni also reaffirmed the country's policy of attracting
foreign investment aimed at more export of finished goods.
</P>
</TEXT>
