<HEADLINE> Takeover Activity Boosts Bonuses Paid to City Bankers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 1 (Xinhua) - The City earned an estimated 1.3
billion pounds (2.08 billion US dollars) in fees during 1997 from
acting on a record 64 billion pounds (102.4 billion US dollars) of
bids.
</P>
<P>
The fees are 200 million pounds (320 million US dollars)higher
than last year, according to Philip Healey, who calculated the
figures for Acquisitions Monthly.
</P>
<P>
British investment banks laid claim to the lion's share of the
spoils in the year, which saw a total of 1801 deals with a
combined value of 64 billion pounds.
</P>
<P>
"The figure not only reflects the large number of deals
completed during the year but also shows that the complexity of
many of the transactions pushed up the costs involved," Healey
said.
</P>
<P>
1997 marked the third consecutive year of strong mergers and
acquisitions activity in Britain, with the highest number of
public bids since 1989.
</P>
<P>
Acquisitions Monthly, put Lazard Brothers at the top of the
league table of City advisers. the UK investment bank advised on
34 transaction with a total worth of 21.9 billion pounds (35.04
billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
SBC Warburg Dillon Read took second place. The Swiss-owned
bank, which announced a 35 billion pounds (56 billion US dollars)
merger with UBS earlier last month, helped to negotiate 19.8
billion pounds (31.68 billion US dollars) worth of UK takeovers.
</P>
<P>
Third place went to Schroders which notched up 12.3 billion
pounds (19.68 billion US dollars) in transactions.
</P>
<P>
City observers believe that the tide of mergers and
acquisitions is sure to boost the level of bonuses paid to City
bankers in the new year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
