<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-01 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli FM Announces to Resign Amid Budget Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Foreign Minister David
Levy today announced to resign over his displeasure with the
draft budget.
</P>
<P>
Levy made public his decision to resign at a news conference
after he had failed to solve the dispute with Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu over the cuts of spendings on welfare in the
budget.
</P>
<P>
Criticizing the planned cuts as "evil policies," he said the
proposed 207 billion-shekel (59 billion U.S. dollars) budget would
not give an answer to the rising unemployment and suffering of the
poor and underclass.
</P>
<P>
The draft budget proposes a cut of 2.6 billion shekels (about
740 million dollars), maily concerning welfare items.
</P>
<P>
Levy, who has long been at odds with Netanyahu over political
and economic policies, said that the five Knesset (parliament)
members of his Gesher Party would vote against the budget.
</P>
<P>
But he refused to speculate if the government would fall if his
party quitted the coalition.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu had so far declined to comment on Levy's decision to
resign, but he was apparently taking it seriously.
</P>
<P>
He had discussed with his aides the possibility of postponing
the vote on the budget till March 31. If he could make it,
Netanyahu would be able to work on another budget and win time to
calm the coalition partners, including Levy.
</P>
<P>
He had hoped to get the budget passed and then announce the
long delayed decision on carrying out troop pullback from the West
Bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
