<HEADLINE> Israeli University Students Strike for Fair </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 1 (Xinhua) -- More than 10,000 university
students throughout Israel took part in a strike today in protest
against increased allocations to yeshiva students in the new
state budget.
</P>
<P>
The National Union of Israeli Students (NUIS), who organized
the strike, said that "it is unthinkable that a parasitic
public receive budgetary increase of dozens of percent, when the
government doesn't relate at all to the university students."
</P>
<P>
The strike is a direct result of Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu's surrendering to the extortion of the religious
parties on behalf of draft-exempt yeshiva students, while most
university students serve in the army and pay over 8,570 U.S.
dollars annually for tuition and board, it said.
</P>
<P>
Several students at the Hebrew University, who also boycotted
classes today, said that the strike is a clear signal that
the university students could not accept the unfair treatment
from the government.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli Knesset (parliament) postponed the vote on the
1998 state budget Wednesday night because several coalition
parliament members threatened to vote against it. 
</P>
