<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ECOMOG Vows to Restore Peace to S. Leone in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 1 (Xinhua) -- The west African peace-keeping
force known as ECOMOG today vowed to resolve the crisis in Sierra
Leone in 1998.
</P>
<P>
In his New Year message, ECOMOG commander Major-General Victor
Malu told his soldiers in Monrovia, capital of Liberia, to see
1998 as a year to extend final peace and stability in Sierra
Leone.
</P>
<P>
According to the British Broadcasting Corporation (BBC), Malu
said the force is the first attempt by west African countries at
conflict resolution.
</P>
<P>
He wished that the force would always do the same to make the
Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS) proud of it at
all times.
</P>
<P>
Dispatched by ECOWAS seven years ago, ECOMOG has helped end
Liberia's bloody civil war, which leads to the successful general
election to make Charles Taylor the first post-war president.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian general expressed his satisfaction that the
dedication of ECOMOG in Liberia has brought abundant security and
peace and drawn investors to the country.
</P>
<P>
This is something that can be done in neighboring Sierra
Leone, he added.
</P>
<P>
Describing 1997 as a very eventful year, Malu commended ECOMOG
soldiers for their exemplary conduct, enthusiastic dedication to
duty, honesty and loyalty.
</P>
<P>
Malu's promise to end the Sierra Leonean crisis comes along
with reports of success by the civil defense group known as
Kamajors against the military junta in the recent fightings in
the east of the troubled country, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The Kamajors is a group of traditional hunters fighting for
the restoration of President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah since his ousting
in a coup in May 25 last year.
</P>
<P>
The militia group has reportedly claimed more areas and seized
additional routes in the northeast over the last few days.
</P>
<P>
In another development, the junta Monday airlifted a group of
journalists to visit a stronghold of the Kamajors in the east of
the country to show its victory in recent fightings with the
hunter militiamen.
</P>
<P>
To flee the fightings, at least 50 people have been reportedly
crossing the Mano River Bridge every day to seek entry in
northwest Liberia.
</P>
<P>
Malu's promise to end the Sierra Leone crisis is seen by
observers as partly expressing the grave concern of the
international community at a time when the peace plan to retore
Kabbah by April this year seems to become something remote.
</P>
</TEXT>
