<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Review 10-year-old Shipping Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's 10-year-old national
shipping policy will soon be reviewed to pave way for a
comprehensive maritime policy, the transport minister has said.
</P>
<P>
"In no distant future, Nigeria will have a comprehensive
maritime policy," Major-General Ibrahim Gumel, Minister of
Transport, told a meeting of the National Maritime Authority
(NMA) in the capital Abuja recently, according to the News Agency
of Nigeria today.
</P>
<P>
The ministry has already set up a committee to review the
policy and work has reached an advanced stage, said Gumel.
</P>
<P>
The minister did not elaborate on the future comprehensive
maritime policy, but stressed the need for the country to start
developing its own maritime fleet so as to remain relevant in the
global shipping industry.
</P>
<P>
He also said the government is looking into the issue
concerning the involvement of indigenous shipping companies in
the lifting of crude oil, liquefied natural gas and other
lucrative imports and exports.
</P>
<P>
NMA has complained that due to the dependence on foreign
shippers, the country loses an estimated eight billion U.S.
dollars annually.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of its own fleet is expected to help improve
the situation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
