<HEADLINE> Hit-and-run Accidents on Rise in Addis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Traffic police in the
Ethiopian capital Addis Ababa today warned that hit-and-run
accidents are on the rise in the city, with 606 such accidents
reported in the last three months.
</P>
<P>
According to the Ethiopian News Agency, Befekadu Tolera, chief
of the Addis Ababa traffic police division, said 14 people have
lost their lives while 244 others sustained heavy and light
injuries in the accidents.
</P>
<P>
Garages, both licensed and unlicensed, and service vehicles
involved in the accidents without having the permit from the
traffic police, has made it difficult to track down the culprits,
he said.
</P>
<P>
He appealed to the public to cooperate with pertinent bodies
by informing on the drivers who escape causing accidents or break
traffic laws.
</P>
<P>
Befekadu also pledged that the traffic police would do their
best to bring the perpetrators to justice.
</P>
<P>
A total of 64 people died and 543 others were injured in the
traffic accidents occurred in the capital city in the last three
months.
</P>
<P>
Drunk driving and failure to give priority to pedestrians were
major causes for the accidents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
