<HEADLINE> Europe to Play Larger Role in Mideast: French </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, January 1 (Xinhua) -- French Defense Minister Alain
Richard said today that Europe would play a larger and more
effective role in the Middle East peace process in 1998, Lebanon's
official National News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Upon his arrival at the Beirut International Airport, Richard
told the press that France would make efforts to help Lebanon
restore sovereignty over its southern part occupied by Israel,
according to the news agency.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a "security zone" in south Lebanon in 1985 to
allegedly protect its northern residents from cross-border attacks
by Muslim guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
The French defense minister stressed that the issue of south
Lebanon was just part of the big problem from which the Middle
East has been suffering, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
He was referring to the deadlock of the peace talks between the
Palestinians, Syrians, Lebanese and Israelis.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine will
visit Lebanon within 10 days, bringing with him important
political ideas about south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Richard arrived here this morning for a one-day visit aimed at
inspecting the French soldiers in the United Nations peacekeeping
force in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Upon his arrival at the airport, he flew by helicopter to the
headquarters of the U.N. peacekeepers in Naquora, a town near the
Lebanese-Israeli border.
</P>
<P>
The 5,400-strong multi-nation U.N. peacekeeping force was
established in 1978 after Israel's first invasion of Lebanon that
year. 
</P>
