<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Angola's Petroleum, Mining Sectors in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, January 2 (Xinhua) -- The year of 1997 has witnessed
encouraging progress in the petroleum and mining sectors of
Angola, the war-torn African country.
</P>
<P>
The official figures show that during last year, daily output
of petroleum in Angola has increased to a record of 750,000
barrels from 600,000 barrels. Its mining sector has begun
recovery and the production of diamond, a main product of the
sector, is expected to reach 1.2 million carat this year and earn
the country 330 million U.S.Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Angola is rich in petroleum, and the petroleum industry is a
major pillar of its economy, so it has always been a strategy of
the Angolan government to develop the petroleum sector and earn
more fund for the development of other sectors.
</P>
<P>
After several years' efforts, all the existing oilfields in
Angola have been put into operation and the petroleum industry
which had been damaged by the civil war has already recovered.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, Angola's daily production of petroleum has recorded a
new high of 750,000 barrels. The figure is expected to reach one
million barrels early in 21st century, according to the Angolan
government's medium term target.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan government has also made great efforts for oil
exploitation. And in this field, the National Petroleum Company
of Angola and Elf-Aquitaine, a French company, have joined their
hands and made several discoveries.
</P>
<P>
Late last year, under the cooperation between the two
companies, a giant deepwater oilfield with a reserve of 100
million tons was discovered offshore, 200 kilometers away from
Luanda, capital of Angola.
</P>
<P>
The two companies also discovered Dalia Oilfield with a
reserve of 700 million barrels in August last year and Girassol
Oilfield with a reserve of 660 million barrels in May, 1996.
</P>
<P>
According to the Ministry of Petroleum, the three oilfields
will be developed in the near future. And the National Petroleum
Company of Angola will also cooperate with other foreign
companies to continue the exploitation of oil in other sea areas.
</P>
<P>
For the development of the petroleum industry, the government
have attached great importance to the restoration and development
of auxiliary enterprises such as Kwanda Oil Logistics Base and
oil refineries.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, in October last year, the Angolan government began
to implement Catoca Program to develop its rich kimberlite
resources. This means that Angola has first developed its
kimberlite resources.
</P>
<P>
At present, the program is still at a pilot phase and the
monthly kimberlite output is 17,000 carat. The program is
expected to be fully implemented early this year and the monthly
production is expected to reach 20,000 carat.
</P>
<P>
In spite of progress made in the two sectors in 1997,
instability in some areas of the country and a large number of
landmines buried underground have become obstacles in the
development of the petroleum and mining sectors.
</P>
<P>
But with the coming of final peace in the country, the two
sectors will have new opportunities to prosper. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980102.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WFP to Boost Relief Operations in Kenya, Somalia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 2 (Xinhua) -- The World Food Program (WFP) is
scheduled to expand its relief operations for flood affected
areas of Kenya and Somalia.
</P>
<P>
A press release issued here today quoted WFP Country Director
for Kenya Mike Sackett as saying that "Major food shortages are
expected over the coming weeks and the emergency situation is far
from over".
</P>
<P>
The WFP has launched phase two of the emergency operation in
Somalia to supply relief food in southern part of the country in
the first three months of 1998.
</P>
<P>
Under the program, the WFP will provide 12,000 tons of food
between January and March at a cost of 6.6 million U.S. Dollars,
</P>
<P>
The Somalia operation which started on November 13 last year
has provided 1,000 tons of food and other relief items to the
worst affected areas by aircraft and 2,000 tons of food drawn
from stocks held in Somalia.
</P>
<P>
The WFP will also provide a total of 8,000 tons of food, fuel
and medicines to stranded communities in Wajir, Mandera, Garissa
and Tana River districts in northeastern Kenya until the end of
February this year.
</P>
<P>
Since the WFP started air deliveries to those districts on
December 10 last year, a total of more than 600 tons of relief
goods have been delivered.
</P>
<P>
The 124,000 refugees in the Dadaab refugee camps in
northeastern Kenya are now totally dependent on air supplies and
the WFP expects to transport 500 tons of food by air every week
to the refugees until the Garissa-Dadaab road link is restored.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's port city of Mombasa and the capital of Eastern
Province, Garissa, serve as main food dispatch point and
operation center for WFP aircraft, which enable the WFP to move
more than 200 tons of food per day to feed 500,000 people in
Kenya and Somalia.
</P>
<P>
The release said that more aircraft are expected to arrive in
January to boost the food relief operations in flood affected
areas in the two countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
