<HEADLINE> East China Province Tackles Financially Troubled State Firms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, January 2 (Xinhua) -- East China's Anhui Province plans
to bid adieu to financially troubled state-owned enterprises
within three years.
</P>
<P>
Of its 520 large- and medium-size state enterprises, 92 have
been losing money for three consecutive years. These companies
have assets of 32 billion yuan and employ 330,000 people,
according to the provincial economic and trade commission.
</P>
<P>
The commission will use mergers and bankruptcies to force
failing companies out of the market while investing funds in those
with growth potential.
</P>
<P>
The commission plans to focus on 60 such enterprises in 1997,
which might result in layoffs of 60,000 workers.
</P>
<P>
By the end of the century, the liability rate of its
state-owned enterprises will be reduced by 10 percent, said the
commission. 
</P>
</TEXT>
