<HEADLINE> Macao, Zhuhai to Share Investment of Link Bridge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Macao and neighboring Zhuhai city,
south China's Guangdong Province, will share the investment half
to half of the planned bridge to link the two places, and the
construction is expected to begin in March, a report said.
</P>
<P>
Thursday's Macao Daily News quoted Zhou Benhui, deputy mayor of
Zhuhai, as saying that the project has passed technical appraisal
of the Chinese side and is under administrative procedure for
approval.
</P>
<P>
He said the bridge will cost a total investment of 400 million
yuan (about 50 million U.S. dollars). Macao and Zhuhai side will
each be responsible for half the investment.
</P>
<P>
The two sides will start construction according to a blueprint
jointly designed, and a joint coordination office will be
established.
</P>
<P>
The planned bridge runs 1,100 meters, with six lanes for
vehicles. It will link the Hengqin Island of Zhuhai and Taipa
Island of Macao.
</P>
<P>
Zhou said that construction of the bridge is expected to begin
in the coming March. It will be completed and put into operation
before the handover of power in Macao in December 1999.
</P>
<P>
The Sino-Portuguese Infrastructure Coordination Commission
finished the geological and hydrological survey of the
construction site last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
