<HEADLINE> Chinese Arts and Crafts Exhibition Opens in Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, January 2 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese Arts and Crafts
Exhibition opened in the National Art Gallery of Sri Lanka here
Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lankan Cultural and Religious Affairs Minister Lakshman
Jayakody, Chinese Ambassador Chen Defu and more than 150 guests
attended the opening ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Jayakody said that written history of more than 20 centuries
between China and Sri Lanka proves how closely the religious and
cultural ties have been maintained between the two nations.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition serves as a memorable milestone in the cultural
exchange program between China and Sri Lanka and will contribute
to the consolidation of the cordial relationship existing between
the two sides, the minister added.
</P>
<P>
Chen Defu, on his part, said both China and Sri Lanka are
ancient countries with civilization and the two have enjoyed an
traditional friendship and cultural exchanges.
</P>
<P>
He said by viewing the exhibited items, the Sri Lankan people
will find more about Chinese culture. Meanwhile, China can also
further understand and learn more from Sri Lanka's resplendent
culture through such kind of cultural exchange.
</P>
<P>
About 300 sets of exhibits, including pottery, cloisonnes,
embroideries, cork carvings, lacquer wares, paintings of Buddhism
figures and so on are on display in the gallery.
</P>
<P>
They are part of the general collections of the handicraft
articles that have been composed by Chinese artists in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
The seven-day exhibition was co-sponsored by the Sri Lankan
Cultural and Religious Affairs Ministry and the China
International Exhibition and Exchange Center.  
</P>
