<HEADLINE> Manila Mayor Gets Party Endorsement for Presidential </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 2 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' Liberal Party
will endorse Manila Mayor Alfredo Lim as its standard-bearer in
the country's May 1998 presidential election.
</P>
<P>
Raul Daza, president of the Liberal Party, told local
television Sky Cable Thursday that the party, one of the country's
oldest political parties, will soon announce its endorsement of
Lim.
</P>
<P>
The move is expected to put an end to the coalition between the
Liberal Party and the ruling Lakas-NUCD (National Union of
Christian Democrats) led by President Fidel Ramos.
</P>
<P>
Lim, a member of the People's Reform Party (PRP), had been
expected to be expelled from the party after declaring his
decision to run for the next presidency in December 1997.
</P>
<P>
Senator Miriam Defensor-Santiago, PRP chief, who herself is set
to join the presidential race, had threatened to expel Lim if he
wanted to press on his presidential bid.
</P>
<P>
Vice President Joseph Estrada, presidential candidate for the
United Opposition, expressed his disappointment for the Liberal
Party's support of Lim, saying the party is a "valuable addition"
to the opposition.
</P>
<P>
Political observers here said the breakaway of the Liberal
Party will not tilt the balance between the administration Lakas
party and the opposition.
</P>
<P>
Daza said the Liberal Party is considering unite with the
so-called "Third Force" which was proposed by Lim and another
presidential aspirant former defense secretary Renato de Villa.
</P>
<P>
Local TV reports said both Lim and the ruling party's candidate
Jose de Venecia, speaker of the House of Representatives, are
wooing Senator Gloria Macapagal-Arroyo as running mate.
</P>
<P>
But Arroyo, another proclaimed presidential contender, has so
far failed to confirm whether she will slide down to run for vice
president. 
</P>
