<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Use of Tibetan Language Spreading in Tibet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, January 2 (Xinhua) -- In present-day Tibet, more than
ten thousand newspapers are being sent every day to people in
cities, counties, farming and stock-breeding areas in their own
language.
</P>
<P>
Tibet currently has 60 kinds of newspapers and periodicals,
half of them Tibetan-language publications. More and more Tibetan
people obtain their information mainly through broadcasting and TV
programs in their own language.
</P>
<P>
Local governments throughout the Tibet Autonomous Region are
encouraging the use of the native language for 2.4 million
Tibetans.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese constitution stipulates that: "Any ethnic
nationality in China has the liberty of using and developing its
own language." A consistent policy of China has been to encourage
the use of the Tibetan language in Tibet, an autonomous region
where more than 94 percent of the population are Tibetans.
</P>
<P>
With a history of 1,300 years, Tibet has a highly developed
language as far as its grammar and expressions are concerned. It
is also a language that has played an important role in the long
history and culture of Tibet.
</P>
<P>
On the streets of Tibet, signs of government organizations,
factories, schools and restaurants are all printed in both Tibetan
and Chinese. Most of the advertising and shops use standardized
Tibetan and Chinese.
</P>
<P>
Service trades such as banks and post offices also use Tibetan.
</P>
<P>
Government documents are written in Tibetan, and papers on
important conferences have two versions. Speakers at conferences
give talks in Tibetan.
</P>
<P>
People also have the right to file lawsuits in their own
language and legislative documents are written in Tibetan.
</P>
<P>
The wide application of software with standard coding in
Tibetan enables the ethnic minority language to gain access to the
Internet, which helps spread the language in the information age.
</P>
<P>
During their six years in primary school, students in Tibet
spend 1,598 hours in learning the local language. They start
learning Chinese in the third grade.
</P>
<P>
In secondary schools as well as colleges, Tibetan is a required
course. The law ensures that students from ethnic minority groups
learn to read and write their own languages as well as
Chinese. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
