<HEADLINE> Chongqing Levies Extra Fee on Tobacco Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Southwest China's municipality
of Chongqing pioneered a campaign to charge extra fees on tobacco
products to fund health education and disease control.
</P>
<P>
Tobacco manufacturers and sellers in Chongqing must pay 0.1
percent of their total sales in extra fees for health care,
according to a regulation published Thursday by the municipal
government.
</P>
<P>
About five million yuan (600,000 U.S. dollars) in fees will be
collected annually.
</P>
<P>
Chongqing is believed to be the first local government taking
such an action. Liaoning and Hubei provinces along with Guangxi
Zhuang Autonomous Region and Shanghai Municipality made the
similar decisions in 1997, but the decisions have not been carried
out yet.
</P>
<P>
Hubei Province planned to levy a 4 percent fee on the sales of
local tobacco products, according to sources from the Ministry of
Health (MOH).
</P>
<P>
"It can on one hand curb the increase of sales of tobacco. On
the other hand, it can fund smoking-control campaigns and solve
financial problems in health-care work," said Cai Renhua, director
of the MOH's Health Policy and Law Department.
</P>
<P>
China's tobacco industry produced 1.7 trillion cigarettes in
1996. The country's 320 million smokers puffed away on 4.8 billion
cigarettes per day, or 240 million packs.
</P>
<P>
The tobacco industry has been a major source for China's
revenue since 1987. It turned out 83 billion yuan (10 billion
dollars) in revenue in 1996, five times that of 1986, according to
a report from the Chinese Academy of Preventive Medicine.
</P>
<P>
A 1993 study showed that if an additional fee of 0.1 yuan was
added to each pack of cigarettes, the state would collect eight
billion yuan (nearly one billion U.S. dollars) -- the figure set
for the national health budget for that year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
