<HEADLINE> HK's Chinese New Year Parade, Fiesta Promises World- </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's coming annual
Chinese New Year's parade is being expanded this year to include a
colorful fiesta aimed at raising the annual celebrations to
world-class status and cementing Hong Kong's position as the
"Events Capital of Asia", organizers said here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The parade will begin on January 28 with around 15 specially
designed and commissioned floats and more than 30 local and
international performing groups along a 1.3 kilometer route in
Tsimshatsui, Kowloon.
</P>
<P>
After the parade, the floats will be lit up immediately at the
Urban Council's Centenary Garden in Kowloon, where they will form
the centerpiece of the two-day Fiesta, on January 28 and 29, the
first two days of the lunar Chinese Year of Tiger, which is open
to the public free of charge, to usher in the Chinese New Year.
</P>
<P>
The Fiesta features such activities as a display of brightly
illuminated floats, stalls and booths for arts and crafts,
traditional snacks, games, food and beverage, as well as live
entertainment performance.
</P>
<P>
The event will introduce the new Mascot Tiger of the Hong Kong
Tourist Association (HKTA) and a mixture of international parade
expertise and the famous Foshan traditional lantern craftsmanship,
as well as the best and most impressive lineup here ever of local
and international performers.
</P>
<P>
Announcing the parade and fiesta featuring a mix of "East Meets
West" elements, the HKTA stressed its commitment to using the
annual event to enhance Hong Kong's position as the world's
capital of Chinese New Year celebrations as well as the "Events
Capital of Asia".
</P>
<P>
Safety has been made a priority, with design and production of
all floats to be centralized and carried out by the event manager
to ensure better quality in design and finishing and that the
safety guideline issued by the government be fully observed.
</P>
<P>
An accident during last year's parade killed one tourist and
injured a few others on a Tsimshatsui pavement.
</P>
<P>
"Safety comes first," stressed an HKTA official.  
</P>
</TEXT>
