<HEADLINE> Hollywood Enjoys Box Office Totals Increase in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Hollywood experienced an
increase of about eight percent in its box office totals in 1997
over 1996.
</P>
<P>
Reports from Hollywood said Thursday U.S. movie-goers spent 6.2
billion U.S. dollars in 1997, another record year, as compared
with 5.8 billion in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Analysts in the industry attribute the jump to products like
"Men in Black" and "The Lost World: Jurassic Park," each grossing
more than 200 million U.S. dollars in North American theaters.
</P>
<P>
The most successful studio in Hollywood was Sony Pictures with
five of its releases "Men in Black," "Air Force One," "My Best
Friends' Wedding" and "I Know What You Did Last Summer" on the top
box office totals list.
</P>
<P>
Economists predict that the growing demand for films and
televisions shows will add 16,000 job to Los Angels in 1998.
</P>
<P>
"We had the thing that every studio dreams of: a film that
satisfied all age groups," said Lucy Fisher, vice-chairperson of
Sony's Columbia Tristar Motion Picture Group.
</P>
<P>
"Entertainment has some of the best prospects (for
employment). It is our shining star," said Jack Kyser, chief
economist of the Los Angeles County Economic Development Corp.
</P>
</TEXT>
