<HEADLINE> Share Prices Decline on Singapore Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Share prices declined on the
Singapore market on the first day of trading in 1998 on Friday, as
the benchmark Straits Times Industrials Index (STII) fell by 11.64
points to close at 1518.2 points.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that the lower share prices in thin trading came
because most fund managers were still sidelined due to the
holidays.
</P>
<P>
Total market volume was thin at 68.2 million units, valued at
111.82 million Singapore dollars (66.17 million US dollars).
Declines overwhelmed advances by 206 to 94, while 309 other
counters remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
MBf Capital was the most actively traded stock as it registered
a turnover of 5.79 million shares. It was followed by Singapore
Telecom which had 2.87 million shares traded. Wing Tai was next
with 2.52 million shares changed hands.
</P>
<P>
Local computer sound card maker Creative 50 led the gainers of
the day as it rose by 1.9 dollars to finish at 36.1 Singapore
dollars. Jurong Shipyard increased by 30 cents to end at 8.3
Singapore dollars, while Asia Pacific picked up by 18 cents to
close at 4.3 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, NatBroad was the biggest loser as it declined
by 59 cents to end at 90 US cents. NBT fell by 54 cents to close
at 2.07 Singapore dollars, while S. Reinsurance lost 31 cents to
finish at 1.09 Singapore dollars.  
</P>
