<HEADLINE> Crime Costs 20 Billion Dollars Last Year in Australia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Crime cost Australians between
18 and 20 billion Australian dollars (13.5 billion US dollars)
last year, federal Justice Minister Amanda Vanstone said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The latest Australian Institute of Criminology estimates found
crime cost every man, woman and child nearly 1,000 Australian
dollars (660 US dollars), or more than four percent of gross
domestic product, Vanstone said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
A total of 3 billion Australian dollars (1.98 billion US
dollars) was spent on police and law enforcement alone, with
another 3 billion going to fight fraud and forgery.
</P>
<P>
Drug offenses cost 2 billion Australian dollars (1.32 billion
US dollars) and shoplifting somewhere between 1 and 2 billion
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
"Crime prevention plays a critical role," she said, adding that
the government was spending 13 million Australian dollars (8.58
million US dollars) on a national campaign against violence and
crime, while the recently announced Tough on Drugs strategy was
also an important anti-crime initiative.
</P>
<P>
"As part of this effort, the government will provide three
federal police strike teams, and more money for informants and
witness protection," Vanstone said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
