<HEADLINE> Hebei Employs 80 percent of Laid-off Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Some 176,000 redundant
workers in north China's Hebei Province were reemployed in the
first 11 months of 1997, accounting for 80 percent of laid-off
workers.
</P>
<P>
The province still faces a re-employment problem of more than one
million surplus urban workers between now and the end of the
century, according to a survey by the Provincial Labor Department.
</P>
<P>
To solve this problem, Hebei has promulgated favorable policies
for laid-off workers, and has raised some 400 million yuan (50
million U.S. dollars) to help them find jobs.
</P>
<P>
"We have set quotas to employers in job fairs to encourage them
to employ qualified laid-off workers," said one local official,
adding that many businesses have helped each other in settling the
job problem of redundant workers.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the province has spent 310 million yuan
during the last two years in training redundant workers and
helping the growth of job placement agencies.
</P>
<P>
To date, the province has more than 152 job placement agencies
and has trained more than 180,000 people.
</P>
<P>
In addition, it has also encouraged laid-off workers to set up
their own businesses. The province has 130-plus centers with
favorable policies for businessmen who were originally surplus
workers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
