<HEADLINE> Malaysia to Send Home Almost Half Registered </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia is expected to
send a million or almost half the number of registered foreign
workers in the country to their respective countries this year
following the move by certain sectors to reduce their workforce
due to the economic slowdown.
</P>
<P>
The foreign workers would be sent home soon after their
retrenchment, Malaysian Deputy Home Minister Tajol Rosli Ghazali
said Friday after presenting the Immigration Department's activity
and work program here.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters that foreign workers still employed would be
distributed among the industries in strategic sectors like
plantations and export-oriented manufacturing industries.
</P>
<P>
He said "This is in line with the government's policy of
reducing foreign workers besides ensuring that they are not
depriving the locals of jobs like in the hospitality industry."
</P>
<P>
Foreign workers in Malaysia are mostly from Indonesia,
Bangladesh, the Philippines and Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The deputy home minister also said that the Immigration
Department would continue raiding workplaces to ensure that
employers were not harboring illegal foreign workers, an offense
under Section 48A of the Immigration Act (Amendment) 1997, under
which, he said, errant employers would have to pay the full cost
of deportation of illegal immigrant workers.
</P>
<P>
According to Tajol Rosli, the number of illegal foreign workers
in Malaysia was estimated at 800,000 and most of them were
Indonesians. 
</P>
