<HEADLINE> Second Malaysia-Singapore Crossing Link Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, January 2 (Xinhua) -- The second
Malaysia-Singapore crossing linking Tanjung Kupang in Malaysia's
Johor and Singapore's Tuas opens Friday, the Malaysian national
news agency Bernama reported.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian Information Minister Mohamed Rahmat said after
observing the first day of operations in Tanjung Kupang that the
opening of the Malaysia-Singapore second crossing is a big start
for 1998 in terms of promoting ties between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
He believed that the crossing linking Tuas in Singapore and
Tanjung Kupang in Johor would greatly benefit relations between
Malaysia and Singapore.
</P>
<P>
He was quoted as saying "We hope that this second crossing will
further enhance friendship, trade and tourism in the southern
region between Malaysia and Singapore."
</P>
<P>
Mohamed said the second link was also expected to ease the
congestion at the present Causeway, the first link opened in June
1924 between Malaysia and Singapore.
</P>
<P>
For a start, only oil tankers heading for Singapore are
required to use the second crossing.
</P>
<P>
The Second Crossing is linked to a 44-kilometer new expressway
leading to Malaysia's North-South Expressway. The new expressway
will allow motorists to by-pass Johor Baharu and head directly to
Singapore or to travel north.
</P>
<P>
The bridge will have a capacity of 200,000 vehicles a day,
which is four times the load on the Causeway and the Second
Crossing is expected to reduce by 30 percent traffic congestion on
the Causeway.
</P>
<P>
Motorists will be able to use the Second Crossing for free for
one month and the toll rates will be announced at the earliest on
January 7, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia and Singapore signed the agreement on the construction
of the second crossing in Kuala Lumpur in March 1994 and the
topping-up ceremony was performed by Malaysian Works Minister
S.Samy Vellu and Singapore's National Development Minister Lim Hng
Kiang in July, last year.
</P>
<P>
Singapore built 0.3 kilometers of the two-kilometer link at a
cost of 600 million Singapore dollars while Malaysia built the
rest, including a six-lane highway to its North-South Highway at a
cost of 1.2 billion ringgit.
</P>
<P>
The bridge components and connecting expressway were privatized
and wholly financed by the developer and concessionaire.
</P>
</TEXT>
