<HEADLINE> Khartoum, Cairo Agree on Tackling Differences </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Sudan and Egypt have agreed on
tackling all their differences to pave way for normalization of
bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
In a statement printed in today's independent Khartoum daily
"Al Gomhouria", Mustafa Osman Ismail, Minister of State at the
Sudanese Foreign Ministry, said that the security organs of the two
countries are intensifying their efforts to close the security
file, preparatory to removing all outstanding obstacles.
</P>
<P>
As a matter of fact, the security file is the most complicated
of all. Egypt is accusing Sudan of giving shelter to active
elements of the Islamic Group of Egypt, and of having been
involved in the attempted assassination of Egyptian President
Hosni Mubarak in the Ethiopian capital city of Addis Ababa on 26
June 1995, and is demanding that the Sudanese government hand over
the files of those elements.
</P>
<P>
Osman revealed that contacts were under way at present between
Cairo and Khartoum to deal with other points of difference
relating to trade, economic and political aspects in the best
interest of the two peoples.
</P>
<P>
He added that after having dealt with these issues, the joint
ministerial committee would be invited to convene in either
capital.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese Minister further stated that the recent resumption
of river navigation between the two countries was the beginning of
full normalization of bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Osman anticipated that Sudanese President Omar Bashir would be
visiting Cairo shortly, and that this visit would be followed by
intensive meetings between officials of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese official expressed hope that Egypt would play a
strategic role in averting the dangers which threatened the
security of the Sudan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
