<HEADLINE> Yellow River Resumes Water Flow in Lower Reaches </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, January 2 (Xinhua) -- For the fourth time China has
been successful in diverting water from the upper and middle
reaches of the Yellow River to the lower reaches that had been
without water for most of 1997.
</P>
<P>
The Yellow River's lower reaches have often run dry in recent
years because of the growing demand for water by cities in the
upper and middle reaches.
</P>
<P>
About 70 million cubic meters of water has been channeled into
the city of Dongying and the Shengli Oil Fields at the Yellow
River's outlet in east China's Shandong Province, according to
official sources.
</P>
<P>
Water flow resumed Nov. 21 at the Lijin Hydrometric Station,
last on the lower reaches of the Yellow River in Shandong Province.
</P>
<P>
The hydrometric station recorded 222 days without water last
year, and some cities at the river's mouth could only supply water
to households for one hour a day.
</P>
<P>
The State Anti-Flood Office and the Yellow River Water
Conservation Committee notified Gansu, Shaanxi and Shanxi
provinces as well as Ningxia Hui and Inner Mongolia autonomous
regions to reduce their consumption of water by 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Sanmenxia and Liujiaxia reservoirs at the upper reaches of
the Yellow River also increased their discharges of water to the
lower reaches.
</P>
<P>
According to weather forecasts, the Yellow River will be short
of water early this year, and officials of the Yellow River
Anti-Flood and Drought Headquarters urged provinces along the
river to conserve their water resources.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980102.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-02 </DATE_TIME>
