<HEADLINE> California Outpaces National Population Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, January 1 (Xinhua) -- California's population
swelled 1.3 percent in the 12 months ending last July 1,
outpacing the national growth rate of 0.93 percent, statistics
show.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Census Bureau said Wednesday that California saw 410,000
more new residents between mid-1996 and mid-1997, by far the
largest in the nation.
</P>
<P>
Analysts attributed California's influx of residents to a
booming and balanced economy that marked the first half of this
decade.
</P>
<P>
While immigration remained a huge factor in the population
growth, the real change was that fewer residents fled
California for other states, they added.
</P>
<P>
The Great Los Angeles area experienced the nation's biggest
population gain between 1990 and 1996, adding 964,000 residents.
</P>
<P>
Mayor Richard Riordan of Los Angeles cited the high growth
rate of population as an indicator of the vibrant economy in the
metropolitan, adding that the city is the place where people want
to live, work and play. 
</P>
</TEXT>
