<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 2 (Xinhua) -- China plans to adopt some new
favorable policies for overseas investors in an effort to boost
the influx of foreign capital.
</P>
<P>
The state is working on a trial basis to open up more channels
to use foreign capital, especially to encourage BOT
(build-operate-transfer) and fund-raising projects, as well as
projects that issue stock overseas, according to the state
Planning Commission.
</P>
<P>
China will continue to open its insurance and commercial retail
business wider to foreign investors, and to work out new policies
to guide overseas capital into mining and other sectors.
</P>
<P>
Foreign businesses or private investors that spend on BOT
projects in 1998 will continue to enjoy favorable policies.
</P>
<P>
Overseas investors can open projects in the central and western
parts of China that are forbidden in the rest of the country by
industrial policies, according to the Office of Special Economic
Zones under the State Council.
</P>
<P>
In addition, overseas investors will be encouraged to cooperate
in building and operating shipping berths, or to solely fund
special sea lanes leading to docks. Joint ventures in ocean
shipping also will be encouraged with foreign investors entitled
to solely funded shipping companies.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that China has approved 300,000 overseas-backed
businesses involving approximately 200 billion U.S. dollars of
investment. And overseas investment makes up more than 20 percent
of the country's total expenditures in fixed assets.
</P>
<P>
Also available for overseas investment are new agricultural
techniques, development of land resources, water conservation,
energy, communications, major raw materials, machinery and
electronics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
