<HEADLINE> Shanghai Tightens Controls on Dangerous Wastes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai is tightening controls
over wastes harmful to the environment and people's health.
</P>
<P>
The city has promulgated two rules concerning the business of
dangerous wastes and their transportation, stipulating that the
municipal environmental protection bureau will have control over
the business and transportation of dangerous wastes.
</P>
<P>
All the units that produce, transport, collect, use and treat
dangerous wastes should accept the supervision and management of
the local environmental department, the rules said.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai has more than 1,000 plants producing dangerous wastes,
with an annual output of 500,000-plus tons, according to the China
Environmental News.
</P>
<P>
These wastes have caused serious pollution in the city, experts
said.
</P>
<P>
The city established a treatment center for dangerous wastes in
1995.  
</P>
