<HEADLINE> Israeli Government Asks US Envoy to Delay Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Israeli government has asked
United States peace envoy Dennis Ross to delay his scheduled
visit here due to the current budgetary crisis, Israel Radio
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Ross was originally scheduled to arrive here next Monday on a
mission to prepare for the pending visits to Washington by Israeli
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) President Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
The radio said Israeli government made the request for delaying
Ross's visit after learning that Ross planned to visit the region
despite the crisis triggered by the budget debate. Israeli and
U.S. officials have been in touch on Ross' visit, and Washington
is expected to accept the Israeli demand since the current crisis
will bind Netanyahu's arms to deal with issues other than the
budget.
</P>
<P>
The Netanyahu government is facing a real crisis of survival
after Foreign Minister David Levy announced Thursday that he
planned to resign if his Gesher Party's budgetary demands are not
met. Due to Levy's threat, Netanyahu decided Thursday night to
postpone the budget vote in the Knesset (Parliament) till Monday.
</P>
<P>
The coalition will be on the verge of collapse if Gesher rebels
are against it, leaving it with only the minimal 61 seats needed
to keep going. The coalition is currently hold a 66 seat majority
in the 120-member Knesset, but at least three hardliners within
Netanyahu's own Likud Party have also threatened to vote against
the government.
</P>
<P>
The delay in budget vote will enable Netanyahu to buy time to
persuade Levy and other rebels within the coalition to refrain
from voting against the government in Monday vote.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu was quoted by the radio as saying today that he would
keep the promises he has made in the past to Levy in a bid to
prevent Levy's departure. He said Finance Minister Yaacov Neeman
has been trying to find extra fund to back up the promises to
Gesher, which is pushing for more money to assist the country's
poor, unemployed and young families.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu hopes to get the budget passed first before dealing
the long delayed issue of carrying out further troop redeployment
in the West Bank. The United States is pressuring Netanyahu to
come out with a redeployment plan by January 15.
</P>
<P>
If Netanyahu fails to get the budget passed in the Knesset,
hardliners within his government will use the redeployment issue
as a bargaining chip for getting more financial gains. 
</P>
</TEXT>
