<HEADLINE> US, UN Try to Resume Bicommunal Contacts in Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, January 2 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. has expressed the
hope that the bicommunal contacts between Greek and Turkish
Cypriot sides will resume shortly.
</P>
<P>
In a statement here today, U.S. Embassy spokeswoman Judith
Baroody said that "without those kinds of people-to-people
contacts, the Cyprus problem cannot be solved."
</P>
<P>
Baroody was commenting on the Turkish Cypriot suspension of
all bicommunal activities, starting from last Saturday, in
reprisal for the European Union's decision to begin membership
talks with the Cyprus government in March 1998, a move that
angered Turkey and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash.
</P>
<P>
Baroody pointed out that Turkish Cypriot restrictions on
these kinds of activities are "incompatible with democracy and a
free society".
</P>
<P>
She added, "we expect, therefore, that the Turkish Cypriot
authorities' review of bicommunal activities be prompt, and that
these activities, which are of such value to Greek Cypriots
and Turkish Cypriots and the future of Cyprus, will resume
shortly and without restrictions."
</P>
<P>
According to local press today, the United Nations are also
making efforts to persuade the Turkish Cypriots to resume
bicommunal contacts.
</P>
<P>
Waldemar Rokoswewski, the spokesman for the U.N. Peace-keeping
Force in Cyprus (UNFICYP), was quoted as saying that "we
believe that Turkish Cypriot authorities should not isolate their
Turkish Cypriot community from either Greek Cypriots or the
outside world."
</P>
<P>
He said there is a generation of people on both sides
of the divide, who do not know each other.
</P>
<P>
That is why, he said, UNFICYP has traditionally supported,
sponsored and arranged virtually hundreds of bicommunal
activities, both in the buffer zone as well as on both sides
of the divide.
</P>
<P>
This East Mediterranean island has remained divided since
Ankara sent troops and took over the northern third in the
wake of a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia in 1974.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. and international community have been trying for
decades to reunite the divided island in a bizonal, bicommunal
federation, but so far little tangible progress has been
achieved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
