<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Research Institute Established For Seed Breeding in Outer Space </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 2 (Xinhua) -- China Aerospace Corp. has
established the first space seed research institute here to
further promote the drive for feeding its 12 billion people.
</P>
<P>
The institute, named "Agricultural Application of Space
Technology Research Institute" under the China Aerospace Corp.,
will conduct research into seed breeding technology in outer space.
</P>
<P>
The technology -- developed in China, Russia, and the United
States in the 1990s -- uses the effects of gravity and air vacuums
to alter chemical bonds, free radicals and DNA chromosomal
structures.
</P>
<P>
Since 1987 Chinese scientists have selected more than 300 types
of seeds from about 50 crops and micro-organisms to send into
outer space.
</P>
<P>
Tests in northeast China's Heilongjiang Province and other
places have shown that rice and wheat output can be increased
8-to-10 percent and vegetable output by 50-to-120 percent using
these techniques.
</P>
<P>
Now in Northeast China's Heilongjiang Province, "space-treated
pepper seeds" were planted on more than 300 hectares.
</P>
<P>
According to experts, China has sent eight batches of crop
seeds into space. The space treatment has been extended to insects
and traditional Chinese herbs.
</P>
<P>
In 1996 Chinese scientists for the first time conducted space
seed breeding for the herb scutellaria baicalensis, the root of
the large-flowered skullcap.
</P>
<P>
Chinese experts said they are expecting to increase crop output
through the breeding of space-treated seeds.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
