<HEADLINE> Qian Qichen Stops Over in HK En Route to Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice Premier and
Foreign Minister Qian Qichen stopped over in Hong Kong today on
his way back to Beijing from his visit to the Middle East and
South Africa.
</P>
<P>
During his brief stopover in Hong Kong, Qian met with Tung Chee
Hwa, chief executive of the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region (SAR) of China, other officials of the SAR government and
members of the Executive Council of the SAR.
</P>
<P>
Tung extended his welcome to Qian and his congratulation on the
establishment of diplomatic relations between China and South
Africa, saying that this is an important event in the history of
relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Tung briefed Qian on the current economic, financial and social
situation in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Tung said that Hong Kong's general economic situation is good
and the SAR government attaches great importance to the prosperity
and stability in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Tung said that the SAR government is taking positive measures
to maintain Hong Kong's prosperity and stability and he is
confident about that.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Qian briefed Tung and officials of the SAR
government on his tour to five Middle East countries and the
establishment of the Sino-South African diplomatic relations.
</P>
<P>
He said that foreign investment and trade in Hong Kong
continued to show a strong momentum and this is a good opportunity
for Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Qian said that Hong Kong's economic fundamentals and financial
management are good and the current economic situation in China's
mainland is also very good.
</P>
<P>
The economy of the mainland will keep a good and healthy growth
rate in 1998, Qian said, adding that this is good for Hong Kong
and also an important support for Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Qian also briefed the Hong Kong officials on the current
international situation and China's recent diplomatic activities.
</P>
<P>
Qian said that there is a consensus in the international
community that China is enjoying economic growth, political
stability and an increasingly important international status.
</P>
<P>
When the world enters the 21st century, China will continue to
follow its independent foreign policy and make efforts to develop
and strengthen friendly and cooperative relations with various
countries and regions, Qian said.
</P>
<P>
Jiang Enzhu, director of the Xinhua News Agency Hong Kong
Branch, and Ma Yuzhen, commissioner of the Chinese Foreign
Ministry in the Hong Kong SAR, were also present at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Qian arrived in Hong Kong this morning and left for Beijing in
the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Qian began his tour to the Middle East on December 18 and
arrived in South Africa on December 28. On December 30, Qian and
his South African counterpart Alfred Nzo signed a joint
communique, in which the two governments agreed to establish
diplomatic relations at ambassadorial level from January 1.
</P>
</TEXT>
