<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Relaunches Debate Over Amsterdam Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 2 (Xinhua) -- France has relaunched the debate
over the Amsterdam treaty on building a tighter European Union
(EU), after the Constitutional Council said on Wednesday that the
ratification of the treaty needs a constitutional amendment
beforehand.
</P>
<P>
The widened version of the Maastricht treaty, adopted by the 15
EU member countries in Amsterdam in June, has been questioned by
many French political groups from the left to the right, because
it covers some sensitive issues like immigration, opening of
frontier and provision of asylum to foreign refugees.
</P>
<P>
In a television interview Friday, Charles Pasqua, the former
interior minister from the Gaullist Rally for the Republic, said
that a national referendum should be held to decide whether the
Amsterdam treaty will be accepted by France or not, because it
concerns the sovereignty of the country.
</P>
<P>
"It is up to the French people and nobody else to decide the
possible abandoning or the transfers of sovereignty. It is the
people that should be consulted," he said.
</P>
<P>
To amend the constitution, President Jacques Chirac can either
call for a joint congress of the two chambers of parliament in
Versaille to vote, or ask for a national referendum.
</P>
<P>
Local media said that Chirac, an ardent supporter of greater
European integration, is more likely to call for a joint congress
of the deputies of the National Assembly and the Senate, as both
chambers have a majority of deputies who support Amsterdam treaty.
</P>
<P>
However, former President Francois Mitterrand had subjected the
French nation to a referendum on September 20, 1992, to decide
whether France should amend its constitution to sign the
Maastricht treaty. A weak majority of 51 percent voted for the
treaty.
</P>
<P>
Most European countries have decided to adopt the Amsterdam
treaty through their parliaments, but some like Denmark prefer the
means of referendum. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
