<DOCNO> XIE19980102.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria's 1998 Budget to Favor Oil Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's 1998 budget, to be
released before or on Saturday, will place the oil sector in a
"better perspective than previous budgets", minister of state for
petroleum resources Alhaji Umaru Dembo has said.
</P>
<P>
Certain provisions in the budget have been made to take care
of the Nigerian National Petroleum Corporation (NNPC) and its
refineries for overall improvement of the nation's economy.
</P>
<P>
Although the provisions "may not be too adequate for now, they
will certainly be a departure from the trends recorded in
previous years".
</P>
<P>
The minister made the remarks during what was called a
familiarization visit to the Kaduna refinery in the north of the
country on Wednesday, according to press reports today.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria is one of the leading oil producers in the world,
turning out about 2.2 million barrels of oil per day, including
condensates.
</P>
<P>
The oil industry accounts for about 95 percent of the
country's total export earnings and about 80 percent of the
federal government revenues.
</P>
<P>
However, progress in the industry is being stalled by
inadequate funding, among other problems, particularly in the
downstream sector.
</P>
<P>
The four refineries of the country, with a total capacity of
445,000 barrels per day, were forced to shut down last year due
to lack of proper maintenance because of fund shortage.
</P>
<P>
For the Kaduna refinery alone, it has become a common
knowledge that the turn-around maintenance work ought to have
been done in 1992.
</P>
<P>
The country now has to import fuel to meet domestic demand
before the maintenance work is expected to end in the first half
of this year.
</P>
<P>
With the budget yet to be presented by the head of state
general Sani Abacha, the minister hinted relevant provisions
would be favorable to the maintenance work of the refineries.
</P>
<P>
That will ensure the steady and uninterrupted supply of
petroleum products, he said, adding that adequate funding in the
oil industry is expected to put the country in a position to
export refined petroleum products. 
</P>
</TEXT>
