<HEADLINE> Coup Plotters Want to Extend Transition, Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian head of state general
Sani Abacha has said that the objective of the foiled December
21, 1997 coup plot is to extend the military regime's transition
to civil rule program scheduled to end October 1 this year.
</P>
<P>
"The objective of the coup attempt was to derail the
transition program and extend the period. I believe that this is
not in our overall interest as a nation, neither is it in our
overall interest as a people," the head of state said, quoted by
press reports today.
</P>
<P>
The alleged coup plotters include Abacha's deputy, chief of
general staff Lt.-gen. Oladipo Diya and 11 others, who are
currently being interrogated under arrest.
</P>
<P>
An unidentified number of people have also been detained in
connection with the botched coup attempt.
</P>
<P>
"If the coup had succeeded, Nigeria would have gone back to
square one in the area of our image and democratic process as
well as scare investors," Abacha told a delegation headed by the
Emir of Fika Alhaji Abali Ibn Mohammed from the northern Yobe
state Thursday in the capital Abuja.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the importance of peace as a pre-requisite for
sustainable development and survival of democracy and assured the
delegation that the transition program was on course and would
not be derailed by the coup plot.  
</P>
</TEXT>
