<HEADLINE> Vietnam Satisfied With Foreign Trade in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam is satisfied with its
achievements in the external trade and commercial activities in
1997, said a senior official.
</P>
<P>
Compared with that of the previous year, the volume of export
increased by over 20 percent. Many key foreign currency earners
considerably raised their export volumes of rice, crude oil,
rubber latex, tea, shoes and seafood, said Deputy Prime Minister
Nguyen Manh Cam in an interview published Friday.
</P>
<P>
Cam, who is in charge of the government's external economic
relations, added that Vietnam has also managed to strictly control
imports and reduce the trade deficit by 37.5 percent down to 2.5
billion U.S. dollars, as compared with the four billion dollars of
trade deficit in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Although direct foreign investment dropped last year, Vietnam
witnessed the highest usage rate of pledged foreign investment in
projects estimated at about 3 billion dollars, he said.
</P>
<P>
However, the deputy prime minister also said that the country
is facing some difficulties in the field of foreign trade and
other commercial activities.
</P>
<P>
Although Vietnam's economic development maintained a high
growth rate, it has been facing many difficulties, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Vietnam in fact has to settle many outstanding problems while
at the same time cope with newly arising difficulties when
entering new stages of development," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
