<HEADLINE> UNIP to Purge Dissidents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, January 2 (Xinhua) -- The United National Independence
Party (UNIP) led by former president Kenneth Kaunda will purge
dissident members creating divisions in the party, vice president
senior chief Inyambo Yeta said here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Times of Zambia quoted him as charging that some leaders are
only interested in monetary gain and are busy creating divisions
instead of consolidating the party.
</P>
<P>
On the same occasion UNIP Lusaka province chairman Peter
Lishika said that even some central committee members are
divisionist and campaigning to have some senior leaders removed.
</P>
<P>
Inyambo said unless discipline is maintained in the party the
situation may deteriorate.
</P>
<P>
In the new year, the party will be tough with the leadership
at all levels.
</P>
<P>
To curb expenditure, salaries and allowances will be reduced,
he said.
</P>
<P>
He said he is greatly dismayed with the level of indiscipline
that has characterized the party, especially in Lusaka province.
</P>
<P>
He castigated leaders for suspending party officials
disregarding the constitution and regulations forcing him to
instruct secretary general Sebastian Zulu to reverse some
suspensions.
</P>
<P>
He told UNIP central committee members to desist from being
arrogant and implored them to tour provinces and not talk down to
members but listen to them.
</P>
<P>
Inyambo said Kaunda has expressed unhappniess with house
arrest describing it as a mere transition from one prison to
another.
</P>
<P>
"Dr Kaunda has asked that we continue the struggle for his
absolute release through the international community." he said.
</P>
<P>
Inyambo said that UNIP will not attend the inter-party talks
until Kaunda is released unconditionally.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda was arrested in connection with the October 28 abortive
coup and released from prison to house arrest on Wednesday
following representations from Tanzanian former president Julius
Nyerere and Zimbabwean president Robert Mugabe. 
</P>
