<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Economic Reforms in Eastern Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Sustained reforms have helped
East European economies recover from its post-Cold War decline,
but ensuing problems are preventing them from achieving a stable
growth.
</P>
<P>
Reforms have been increasingly painful for the economies in
transition but not efficacious enough to restore them to their
pre-1989 level.
</P>
<P>
A World Bank report predicted the economic growth in East
Europe to be 3 percent in 1997, slightly up from the previous
year.
</P>
<P>
Poland, a front-runner in the transition to market-oriented
economy, expected its gross domestic product to grow by 6 percent
last year. Despite international sanctions, Yugoslavia's gross
domestic product was expected to grow by 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Hungary's GDP growth rate was estimated at 3 percent. It has
been ambitious in its reform program. By the end of 1997, only
five enterprises in the country remained state-owned. Half of its
exports are now produced by foreign-owned ventures.
</P>
<P>
The Czech Republic's GDP was predicted to grow by 1.8 percent
last year and the government decided to quicken the restructuring
of enterprises in the public sector.
</P>
<P>
Privatization would move ahead -- but not without a price.
</P>
<P>
The opening of their economies to global competition after
years of planned economy has been painful, with soaring trade
deficits, growing unemployment and an economic growth far below
the average of the of the developing world.
</P>
<P>
East European economies are also troubled by budget deficit,
tax collection problems, soaring inflation and lack of social
security network for the poor.
</P>
<P>
With those problems, the economic growth in the region remained
unstable and fragile. The growth rate of the Czech economy slowed
down last year following a strong rebound since 1994. The
Hungarian economy also experienced ups and downs in the past four
years.
</P>
<P>
The economy in Romania and Bulgaria did not fare well and
Albania's economy was on the verge of collapse following social
turmoil early last year. Bosnia has yet to rebuild its economy
after four years of devastating war.
</P>
<P>
In East Europe, 10 countries voiced their interest in joining
the European Union, but their per capita GDP was only 32 percent
of that of EU member nations. EU decided in July that it would
start membership talks with Poland, the Czech Republic, Hungary,
Slovania and Estonia. Observers believe the five East European
nations will have to need conduct more economic restructuring
before they could join the EU.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that deeper reforms are needed for coping with the
problems of the economies in transition.
</P>
<P>
They observe that the East European economies still have a long
way to go before they could step into a period of stable and
sustained growth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980102.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-02 </DATE_TIME>
