<HEADLINE> Rose Parade Marks New Year's Day in U.S. City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, January 1 (Xinhua) -- One million people flanked
Colorado Blvd in Pasadena, California, and 400 million sat before
TV sets around the world, watching the 109th Rose Parade on New
Year's Day, organizers said.
</P>
<P>
The annual Rose Parade, which is a traditional way of
celebrating the first day of a new year, was a two-hour procession
of the flower-draped floats as well as marching bands and
equestrian units along the five-and-half-mile Colorado Blvd, a
famous route in Pasadena.
</P>
<P>
This year, 54 floats made of roses, 22 marching bands chosen
from high schools and 26 best equestrian units paraded and were
cheered by some 1 million people, who gathered there overnight
from all parts of the United States.
</P>
<P>
Organizers said that an estimated TV audience of 425 million
people in more than 100 countries were watching the event this
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
