<HEADLINE> Bangladesh's Letters of Credit Reach 2.11 Bln Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's letters of credit
(LCs) reached 95.47 billion taka (2.11 billion US dollars) during
the first four months of the current fiscal year (July 1,
1997-July 1, 1998), according to a statement released Thursday by
the central bank, Bangladesh Bank.
</P>
<P>
The value of the LCs reflected an increase of 8 percent over
that of the same period of the previous fiscal year, said the
statement.
</P>
<P>
The total value of outstanding LCs till October 30, 1997 stood
at 96.86 billion taka (2.14 billion dollars), according to the
statement.
</P>
<P>
The LCs for the import of textile fabrics and accessories for
the garment industry were highest in volume, valued at 25.49
billion taka (563.3 million dollars) during the period under
review.  
</P>
