<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan President Set to Be Re-Elected </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Incumbent Kenyan President
Daniel arap Moi is set to win the country's second multi-party
elections whose ballot counting is expected to be concluded
today.
</P>
<P>
So far Moi has garnered more than two million votes and got
the simple majority of 25 percent of the vote in six provinces,
according to the latest local media reports.
</P>
<P>
Under Kenya's law, the candidate who wins the highest total
and collects at least 25 percent of the votes in at least five of
Kenya's eight provinces can be qualified as a president.
</P>
<P>
Electoral Commission (EC) Public Relations Officer Mahamed
Koor told Xinhua the EC could not give the official results
unless vote counting is finished in all constituencies.
</P>
<P>
Only the capital city of Nairobi and Central Province, which
is the power-base of Kibaki, continued to elude Moi.
</P>
<P>
Based on initial results from 170 out of 210 constituencies,
Moi headed the poll with 2.013 million votes, followed by
Democratic Party Chairman Mwai Kibaki with over 1. 65 million
votes, said the latest Kenya Television Network's report.
</P>
<P>
However, Moi's expected win has caused mixed reactions from
opposition groups.
</P>
<P>
Kibaki and National Development Party's leader Odinga
announced Thursday they would not accept Moi as a winner while a
leading opposition lobby group, the National Convention Executive
Council (NCEC), said the poll "must be declared null and void."
</P>
<P>
However, they failed to reveal their further plans, if they
had any, in case of a Moi victory.
</P>
<P>
The government warned later that the police would "deal
swiftly and firmly" with anyone who tried to disturb the peace.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, both Moi's ruling Kenya African National Union and
main opposition parties claimed the elections had been rigged,
saying the poor organization of the polling by the EC offered
advantages to their rivals.
</P>
<P>
Transport difficulties caused by bad weather, mixed ballot
papers, missing electors names from registers, lack of ballot
papers and other technical problems caused delays, chaos and
tension nationwide in Monday's poll and forced one-day extension
of the voting.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, the U.S. administration said despite
"bureaucratic flaws" in the polling process, "the Kenyan people
through their actions have demonstrated a powerful commitment to
democracy."
</P>
<P>
"We are encouraged by the level of peaceful, popular
participation in the election" in Kenya, U.S. State Department
Deputy Spokesman James Foley was quoted by reports reaching here
as saying.
</P>
<P>
A total of 9,031,141 registered Kenyan voters were expected to
to elect one president, 210 parliamentary members and 2,955 local
councillors for the next five years starting from 1998.
</P>
<P>
There are 883 candidates from 23 parties running for the
parliamentary seats while 8,446 for civic positions in the
country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
