<HEADLINE> Zambia's Opposition Party Demands Its Leader's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, January 2 (Xinhua) -- The opposition Zambia Democratic
Congress (ZDC) demanded Thursday release of its leader Dean
Mung'omba one day after former President Kenneth Kaunda was put
under house arrest from prison.
</P>
<P>
ZDC General Secretary Stanley Hamusonde said that "we are
disappointed that President Chiluba refused to free Mung'omba
because outsiders did not ask about his release, this is sad as
it gives an impression that Chiluba can only act when foreigners
intervene."
</P>
<P>
He said that Chiluba should be able to act on his own without
waiting for outside pressure.
</P>
<P>
Hamusonda said it is unfair for the ZDC leader to remain in
prison for two months now while Kaunda who was only seven days
behind bars was released.
</P>
<P>
Announcing Kaunda's release Wednesday from prison to house
arrest Chiluba said he decided to place Kaunda under house arrest
leaving out the others like ZDC President Mung'omba because the
outcry was on Kaunda, who was arrested last Thursday allegedly in
connection with the October 28 abortive coup, and none of the
others were mentioned.
</P>
<P>
Mung'omba was arrested on October 31 in connection with the
coup attempt. 
