<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Ends Slightly Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 2 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar limped
into New Year trading pressured by falling gold prices, only just
managing to cling to the 65 US cents level.
</P>
<P>
But traders are bearish on the outlook for the local currency,
predicting it will slide below the figure when the market returns
to full strength next week.
</P>
<P>
The local currency finished the week at 65.06 US cents, down
from 65.24 locally on Wednesday, New Year's Eve.
</P>
<P>
John Reedyk, head of foreign exchange sales with ANZ bank,
expects the Australian dollar to re-test 64.60 US cents next
week.
</P>
<P>
The currency was last seen at that level on December 16, when
it plunged to a four-year low.
</P>
<P>
Australia's Colonial State Bank Chief Economist Craig James
said the effects of weaker Asian economies and more competitive
Asian exports would gradually result in a weaker Australian trade
position over 1998.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar ended the week at 85.19 yen, from 84.76
here on Wednesday and at 1.1722 marks, from 1.1672.  
</P>
