<HEADLINE> New Ruble To Ease the "Paper Chase" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, January 1 (Xinhua) -- A new ruble, worth 1,000 times
more than the old, began circulating in Russia on Thursday, the
first day of 1998.
</P>
<P>
With the new ruble came the reappearance of the kopeck. The old
kopeck, the smallest coin in the Russian currency, was taken out
of circulation six years ago.
</P>
<P>
The newly-issued ruble includes five kinds of paper currency of
5, 10, 50, 100 and 500 rubles notes, and three kinds of coin
rubles. There are four kopeck coins.
</P>
<P>
At the present, the rate of the new ruble is six against one
U.S. dollar. The old ruble was 6000 to one dollar.
</P>
<P>
Though the new ruble is circulating, the old money is also
being allowed to continue circulating in 1998. Banks will accept
old notes for exchange for another four years.
</P>
<P>
It was expected about 90 percent of the old notes would
disappear from circulation after the first month this year, and
the new bills would fully replace the old by the middle of this
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980102.0114 </DOCNO>
