<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Guarantees Rights of Merged Bank Clients </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Bank Indonesia, the central
bank, pledged it will guarantee all rights and obligations towards
clients of four state-run banks which will merge before July 31,
1998.
</P>
<P>
According to a Bank Indonesia press release received Friday,
the merger process will not stop bank activities process.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia announced Wednesday that it would merge four of the
seven state-run banks and open all of them to foreign ownership as
it moved ahead with key banking reforms.
</P>
<P>
"As part of the series of economic reform policies, especially
to bring health into the banking sector, the government is going
ahead with the merger of state banks," Finance Minister Mar'ie
Muhammad said when making the announcement.
</P>
<P>
According to the government decision, Bank Pembangunan
Indonesia, Bank Bumi Daya, Bank Dagang Negara and Bank Ekspor
Impor Indonesia will be merged into a single new bank.
</P>
<P>
During the process of the merger and after its completion, the
rights and services to clients of the banks continue to be honored
and executed, as usual, according to the existing agreement, said
the release.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the rights and obligations pertaining to foreign
transactions would be fully honored and executed in accordance
with the respective agreements, it added.
</P>
<P>
It said that the clients of the merged banks automatically
become the clients of the single new bank.
</P>
<P>
The government decision to merge the four state banks is the
second step to make the country's banking system more efficient
and healthy.
</P>
<P>
On November 1, 1997, the government closed 16 insolvent private
banks as part of its economic reform package supported by the
International Monetary Fund (IMF).  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
