<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia to Take G-77 Chair </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia is for the first time
to assume the chairmanship of the Group of 77, the negotiating
forum of developing countries at the United Nations, officials at
the Foreign Ministry confirmed here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's turn to head the group will begin with a ceremony
handing over the post from the Tanzanian foreign minister to
Indonesian Foreign Minister Ali Alatas at the UN headquarters in
New York on January 12, said the officials.
</P>
<P>
The ceremony is expected to be attended by UN Secretary General
Kofi Annan, the executive administrator of the UN development
Program and other heads of UN agencies, they added.
</P>
<P>
Ambassador and Permanent Representative of Indonesia to the UN
Makarim Wibisono said earlier that as chairman of the 133-member
group, Indonesia will have a special chance to offer alternative
approaches to developing countries as they prepare for the next
millennium, fraught as it will be with challenges and
opportunities in areas of multilateral economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
In electing Indonesia to chair the group, G-77 members recalled
the country's skippering of the Nonaligned Movement, steering that
group's strategy away from confrontation to partnership with
developed countries.
</P>
<P>
"The G-77 chairmanship gives Indonesia a chance to review the
Caracas Program of Action (CPA), upon which the G-77 was founded,
to determine whether or not it remains valid," Makarim said.
</P>
</TEXT>
