<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cigarette Maker Pays Big Sum for Smoking-Related Death </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, January 1 (Xinhua) -- A United States' tobacco
company has paid 1.5 million U.S. dollars to the family of a Los
Angeles psychologist who died of lung cancer linked to cigarettes
he smoked in the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
Milton Horowitz sued the Lorillard Tobacco Company after a rare
form of asbestos-related lung cancer was diagnosed in 1994. He
said he became sick because the Kent cigarettes he smoked during
the 1950s contained asbestos filters.
</P>
<P>
A San Francisco jury in 1995 awarded Horowitz, then 70, and his
family 1.3 million dollars in compensatory damages and 700,000
dollars in punitive damages.
</P>
<P>
The company appealed the verdict but both a state appeals court
and the California Supreme Court upheld the verdict.
</P>
<P>
Horowitz's children took over the lawsuit after their father
died in 1996. Earlier this week, two years after the jury verdict,
the company paid the compensatory portion of the award, which with
interest and trial cost came to 1.5 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
They are believed to be the first Americans to collect a
smoking-related judgment from a cigarette company. Opponents
against tobacco industry hailed it as an important milestone in
their fight. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
