<DOCNO> XIE19980102.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singaporeans Suffer Record Cases of Dengue, Malaria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, January 2 (Xinhua) -- The number of cases of
mosquito-borne diseases, particularly dengue fever and malaria,
hit a record high in Singapore in 1997, showing that Singaporeans
have not been spared the resurgence of dengue in the region, the
Straits Times reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Citing statistics from the Environment Ministry, the Straits
Times said that there were 4,300 dengue fever cases last year and
one person died of it. In 1996, there were 3,128 cases and three
people died.
</P>
<P>
Dengue is transmitted by the Aedes mosquito, which breeds in
clean and stagnant water, such as rain water that collects in
discarded containers in gardens and homes.
</P>
<P>
As there is no vaccine against dengue, the ministry's focus is
on controlling the Aedes mosquito population. In order to help
stem the rise in dengue fever cases, the fine for breeding
mosquitoes was doubled in October last year to 100 Singapore
dollars (about 59 U.S. dollars) for first-time offenders, while
repeat offenders are fined 200 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
Last year also saw an increase in the number of malaria cases
to 421 from 364 in 1996. About 90 percent, or 386 cases, of them
were imported. Some were brought in by Singaporeans who had
traveled overseas but most were from foreigners working here, on
tour here, or who came here to seek medical treatment, the Straits
Times report said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
