<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibet Economy Up 13.4 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, January 2 (Xinhua) -- The economic growth in the Tibet
Autonomous Region is estimated at 13.4 percent for 1997, far
outpacing the national average of 8.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
This would be the fifth consecutive year that Tibet has
registered double-digit economic growth, which would give the
remote region a stronger mandate to improve people's living
standards and infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
Tibet's total gross domestic product (GDP) is estimated at
7.35 billion yuan for 1997.
</P>
<P>
Local economists attributed the rapid GDP growth to a dramatic
surge of investment in basic industries and infrastructure, a
direct result of central government support, more efforts for
reform and opening up, and aid from the inland provinces and
municipalities.
</P>
<P>
In 1997 Tibet pumped 400 million yuan into agriculture and, as
a result, achieved major gains in its grain harvest.
</P>
<P>
Per capita income of Tibetan herdsmen and farmers should rise
to 1,040 yuan in 1997 from 975 yuan the previous year. And 120,000
residents should rise from poverty, lowering the number of
poverty-stricken people in the region to 330,000. China's poverty
line now stands at 550 yuan in terms of annual per capita income.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Tibet also accelerated the pace of economic reforms
and industrial restructuring, which, in part, contributed to the
region's rapid economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, local officials said, key construction projects
proceeded smoothly last year, with investment rising to 3.67
billion yuan from 2.38 billion yuan in 1996. So far, 60 out of the
62 state-funded key projects have been completed and put into
operation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980102.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Treatment of Hemophilia B Developed by Chinese Doctors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, January 2 (Xinhua) -- A new way of treating
hemophilia B has been developed by doctors at a Shanghai hospital.
</P>
<P>
The new technique to treat the blood disease with gene transfer
was the result of long-term cooperation between Shanghai-based
Fudan University and the Changhai Hospital attached to the No. 2
Medical University of the Chinese People's Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
Examinations of two patients who received the gene-transfer
therapy six years ago, have shown that their health is quite good
with no side effects or complicating diseases.
</P>
<P>
Hemophilia B is a hereditary disease caused by blood that is
short of Factor IX plasma thromboplastin component
(PTC). Spontaneous bleeding and a weakened ability to form new
blood cells are symptoms of the disease. Most patients rely on
blood transfusions or blood products to complement blood-forming
factors. Patients are often threatened by viral infection.
</P>
<P>
Using the gene-transfer technique, doctors inject cells taken
from the patient and cultivated outside the patient's body with
blood-forming genes into the blood of patients.
</P>
<P>
Four boys, aged 4 to 15, have received such treatment since
1991, and their blood-forming function is now effective.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980102.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Well Drillers Praised in Ethiopia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, January 2 (Xinhua) -- The General Manager of
Addis Ababa Water and Sewerage Authority, Tadesse Kebede, has
praised as the "best quality" of the well drilling project
constructed by China National Complete Plant Import and Export
Group.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a farewell reception he gave yesterday evening
here for the Chinese team who just completed the 27 well drilling
project before the eve of new year, Tadesse said he was "very,
very happy for the completion of the project."
</P>
<P>
Tadesse described the well-drilling project as a friendship
between the peoples of Ethiopia and China and hoped the
cooperation between them will be continued in the future.
</P>
<P>
Tadesse said that the well drilling project is a very
important project for the authority and it will play an important
role in alleviating the water shortage of the capital city.
</P>
<P>
According to Tadesse, Addis Ababa is a city short of water and
the current water supply is only 60 percent of its needs while
the shortage is 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
To alleviate the water shortage of the city, the authority is
carrying out an emergency groundwater development project
following the completion of the wells.
</P>
<P>
The first phase of the project, laying water pipes for 11
wells is expected to be completed at the end of 1998 while the
second phase of the project for the remaining 14 wells will
invite bidders at the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
The 25 wells project will supply 25-30 percent water needs of
the city, raising the water supply rate of the city from
currently 60 percent to 85-90 percent.
</P>
<P>
Outside the city, another 27 wells located at Akati, 15 kms
south of Addis Ababa, were completed a week ago after two years
hard work by Chinese constructors.
</P>
<P>
Project Manager Li Lei told Xinhua that the average yield of
the 120-to-150m-deep wells in the capital city, is 7,200 cubic
meter per day per well.
</P>
<P>
The 13-men Chinese team is appreciated by the project owner
and other related departments because they complete the project
on time under the conditions of insufficient technical
information and outmoded equipment, especially the complicated
geological conditions of the well site.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
