<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Govt Against Child Labor in Mining </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, January 2 (Xinhua) -- The Tanzanian government
has warned miners of employing child labor, the Guardian said
today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a symposium which closed here Thursday, the
Minister for Community Development, Women and Children Affairs,
Mary Nagu, said the government will "take stern measures" against
those who employ children in mining.
</P>
<P>
"The government wants to alert you to stop employing children.
Instead, you are advised to let them proceed with their studies,"
Nagu was quoted by the newspaper as saying.
</P>
<P>
She made the remarks at the symposium which was organized by
Tanzania Women Miners' Association. It was attended by
representatives from Kigoma, Morogoro, Mbeya, Shinyanga, Tanga
and Mara regions.
</P>
<P>
But the minister gave no details on the punishment of those
miners who employ children as cheap labor.
</P>
<P>
Although child labor has been widely criticized in Tanzania, a
number of small-scale miners prefer to employ children. Teenage
boys who are flexible in exploiting coal out of smaller pits have
been described as "snake boys," who are more efficient than
adults in this aspect.
</P>
<P>
According to a United Nations Development Program report
released last month, only 15 percent of primary school leavers
joined schools in 1996, a very low rate compared with other
sub-Saharan African countries.
</P>
<P>
The minister also urged women miners to form a broad network
with other miners in other countries to form a broad network so
as to boost the the development of minerals.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
