<HEADLINE> Philippines Optimistic About Dealing With Financial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 2 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of the
Philippines Friday expressed optimism that the country will be
able to cope with the continuous devaluation of the peso against
the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
Central Bank governor Gabriel Singson said the situation is
still within manageable levels, especially with the government's
imposition of some belt-tightening and other economic measures
that would arrest the further plummeting of the peso.
</P>
<P>
Previously, the government had taken significant steps to
reform the local financial system to "dismantle regulations that
tend to hamper growth and to create a more investor-friendly
investment atmosphere", he said.
</P>
<P>
These reforms include interest rate liberalization,
rationalization of the reserve requirement, establishment of new
banks and branches, financial restructuring of the Central Bank
and the entry of foreign banks.
</P>
<P>
He added that these measures had affected the behavior of a
number of key economic indicators such as interest rates, savings
and growth in the country.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he said the International Monetary Fund has also
agreed to grant a new loan of 1.8 billion U.S. dollars to help
sustain the Philippines' financial market.
</P>
<P>
The peso has fallen by 52 percent from 26.2 pesos a dollar to
the current level of 40.116 pesos per dollar since July last year,
causing interest rates to soar and damping the growth of local
industries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
