<HEADLINE> Australia to Help PNG Rehabilitate Crops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Australia will donate almost
500 ton of plants and seeds to Papua New Guinea (PNG) as part of a
one million Australian dollar (650,000 US dollar) program to help
the country rehabilitate crops after last year's devastating
drought and frosts.
</P>
<P>
The decision to provide fast-growing crops to PNG villagers
came as AusAid, Australia's official overseas agency, and the
Australian Defense Force prepare for the start of a third cycle of
emergency food deliveries on Saturday to isolated areas of the
Pacific nation.
</P>
<P>
The new agricultural rehabilitation program would assist the
long-term recovery of PNG food crops, Australian Foreign Minister
Alexander Downer said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Up to 695,000 people in PNG have entered 1998 at risk of
starvation because of severe drought in the country, Care
Australia, a leading aid agency, said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"By beginning to replant village food gardens the project aims
to reduce the dependency on emergency food relief supplies by
helping villagers develop a more secure, sustainable food supply,"
Downer said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Under the rehabilitation project, Australia will ship plant and
seeds of rapid growing food crops.
</P>
<P>
Since last October, Australia has airlifted more than 1.2
million kg food to isolated areas of PNG facing serious food
shortages due to widespread crop failures caused by drought and
killer frosts last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
