<HEADLINE> Bangkok Subway to Proceed: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 2 (Xinhua) -- The Thai government will not
shelve the multi-billion-baht Bangkok underground train project
but will press on with it, the Bangkok Post reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister's Office Minister Somboon Rahong said Thursday
the government is seeking financial support from Japan's Overseas
Economic Cooperation Fund for the 20-km project.
</P>
<P>
"The government will not suspend the project. It will proceed
on schedule... The system should start service in the year 2002,"
Somboon was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, the National Economic and Social Development
Board, the country's economic planning agency, suggested that the
project be shelved to save money.
</P>
<P>
Somboon said delaying the mass transit project will do more
harm than good. Losses through traffic congestion, wasted fuel and
pollution are tremendous, adding that the state would face much
higher construction costs of the project if it was to be
postponed.
</P>
<P>
The minister revealed that he is asking the Japanese fund to
lend 80 percent of the project's civil work construction cost (70
billion baht, or 1.5 billion US dollars at current exchange rate),
instead of an earlier agreed 60 percent.  
</P>
