<HEADLINE> Thailand's Tourist Arrivals Up Less Than 1 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Foreign tourist arrivals in
Thailand grew less than 1 percent in 1997, far below the 7 percent
increase forecast earlier in the year, the Bangkok Post reported
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The slowdown in the tourism industry was due to the economic
crisis in several Asian countries and the haze that covered
Southeast Asia in October and November, the newspaper quoted Seree
Wangpaichitr, governor of the Tourism Authority of Thailand (TAT),
as saying.
</P>
<P>
Seree added that the cheap baht did not attract foreigners to
Thailand as much as the TAT had projected.
</P>
<P>
He said tourists buying package tours to Thailand did not
benefit at all, as tour operators never reduced their prices, some
hotels quoted their room rates in US dollars, and overseas tour
companies and their local partners pocketed huge exchange-rate
profits instead of passing the savings along to consumers.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the low arrival growth in 1997, the TAT has
reduced its foreign tourist arrival target for the two-year
"Amazing Thailand" (1998 and 1999) tourism campaign, from 17
million arrivals down to 16 million, with 7.66 million arrivals
expected in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The two-year tourism revenue target has also been cut from 600
billion baht to 582 billion baht (or 13 billion US dollars to
12.65 billion dollars at current exchange rate).
</P>
<P>
Tourism industry officials believe that 1998 will be another
tough year for the sector.  
</P>
</TEXT>
