<HEADLINE> China's Athletes Break 29 World Records in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 2 (Xinhua) -- China's athletes had a harvest
year in 1997 when they smashed 29 world records and won 92 world
champions.
</P>
<P>
These world records were rewritten by 29 people and two teams,
some of them improved more than once.
</P>
<P>
The new marks include four in swimming, 24 in weightlifting and
one in short-track speed skating.
</P>
<P>
These brought the total of the world records smashed or
surpassed by Chinese athletes to 880 since the founding of the New
China in 1949.
</P>
<P>
The number of the world champions was increased to 1123.
</P>
<P>
Weightlifter Chen Jingkai became the first Chinese to hold a
world record after he lifted 133 kilograms for jerk in the
56-kilogram category in 1956.
</P>
<P>
The country's first world title came in 1959, when Rong Guotuan
won the men's singles title at the 25th World Table Tennis
Championships in 1959. 
</P>
