<HEADLINE> Shanghai Dealing With Urban Sewage Problems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai is expediting an
urban sewage treatment project in a bid to improve the quality of
the city's drinking water.
</P>
<P>
Initiated in the mid-1980s, the first phase was completed in
the early 1990s on the upper reaches of the Huangpu River and the
north bank of the Suzhou River, two major drinking water sources
for Shanghai city dwellers.
</P>
<P>
More than 800 million yuan (96 million U.S. dollars) has been
spent shifting the city's major water intakes to the middle
reaches of the Huangpu River.
</P>
<P>
An additional 2.5 billion yuan (301 million U.S. dollars) has
been spent to block industrial and residential wastewater from
flowing into the Suzhou River, and to erect a 40-kilometer-long
underwater pipeline with a daily sewage transporting capacity of
1.4 million cubic meters. An area of 70 square kilometers and a
population of more than one million have benefited from the sewage
treatment project.
</P>
<P>
In recent years the focus has shifted to building reservoirs
and water treatment plants. The Chenhang Reservoir on the Yangtze
River now supplies 400,000 cubic meters a day to the metropolis.
</P>
<P>
In the first half of 1997, the city government embarked on the
project's second phase. At this stage, 4.8 billion yuan (578
million U.S. dollars) is being spent to extend a pipe 50
kilometers into the depths of the mouth of Yangtze River to
transport urban sewage.
</P>
<P>
The project is scheduled for completion by 1999, when the pipe
will have a daily capacity of 1.7 million cubic meters and benefit
an area of 270 square kilometers and 3.56 million Shanghai
residents.
</P>
<P>
Work on clearing a layer of mud in the Suzhou River is also
under way at an estimated cost of 20 billion yuan (2.4 billion
U.S. dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
