<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese, US Scientists to Hold Seminar on Most Frontier Subjects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Young Chinese and American
scientists will discuss the latest developments in frontier
sciences for the first time at a seminar this year.
</P>
<P>
Forty young Chinese scientists will attend a seminar on
frontier sciences to be held in California of the United States in
August.
</P>
<P>
The Sino-U.S. seminar will offer seven fields for
discussion: geology, physics, chemistry, biology, mathematics,
social sciences and astronomy. The organizing committees of China
and the United States will make a final decision next month on the
specific contents to be discussed at the August seminar.
</P>
<P>
By informing each other of the latest scientific developments,
Chinese and American scientists are expected to enlighten each
other and share ideas to break down barriers they face at work,
and to open new research areas.
</P>
<P>
The Sino-U.S. seminar is the offshoot of a national seminar on
frontier sciences that has been going on since 1989 in the United
States. Three or four U.S. scientists will be selected to make
reports in non-professional language on their latest discoveries
and the growth of research fields at the seminar.
</P>
<P>
Bai Chunli, vice-president of the Chinese Academy of Sciences
(CAS), was very much impressed by the US seminar when he attended
the ninth one held in November of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Bai believes that it is a good challenge for Chinese scientists
to participate in such academic exchanges in terms of knowledge,
language, communications and organizing capabilities.
</P>
<P>
The CAS, China's top natural science research body, is working
on member selection for the seminar. Candidates do not have to be
CAS members, Bai said.
</P>
<P>
Bai said he hopes that the most competitive scientists will
pass the examination and attend the seminar on behalf of Chinese
scientists. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
