<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Balloonist Flows off U.S. Land </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 1 (Xinhua) -- U.S. balloonist Steve Fossett
smoothly flew off U.S. territory Thursday in his third attempt to
circle the globe by non-stop ballooning.
</P>
<P>
By 5:30 p.m EST (22:30 GMT), Fossett was about 110 kilometers
southeast of Bermuda, traveling at about 128 kilometers per hour
at an altitude of 6,640 meters. He was expected to reach Europe by
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
What he was concerned on Thursday was about the safety of his
competitor Kevin Uliassi, who took off a few hours after Fossett
Wednesday night but was forced to abort his attempt.
</P>
<P>
Fossett took off from Busch Stadium in St. Louis and Uliassi
from a quarry near Rockford, Illinois. Three hours after takeoff,
a burst helium container forced Uliassi to abort and land, unhurt,
in Indiana.
</P>
<P>
Fossett, 53, was trying to become the first person to
successfully pilot a balloon around the globe.
</P>
<P>
The last time was in January 1997, also after a Busch Stadium
takeoff.
</P>
<P>
Although he failed to cross the Pacific Ocean because of
shortage of fuel in the last try, he set a record by traveling
16,000 kilometers in six days without stop.
</P>
<P>
This time he is carrying 50 percent more fuel and his balloon
is 28 percent larger at 9,800 cubic meters.
</P>
<P>
He will burn an ethane and propane fuel mixture to heat air
surrounding the helium encapsulated in the balloon and thus
control his altitude.
</P>
<P>
Fossett has oxygen mask and a separate heating system for the
unpressurized capsule to survive in the thin air and the upper
altitude temperatures that drop as low as as minus 45.4 Celsius.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
