<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Acts to Protect Local Manufacturers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos
has ordered the country's top economic managers to draw up a
rescue plan for local manufacturers to avert possible massive
layoffs and conserve precious foreign exchange.
</P>
<P>
Ramos issued the order following a proposal from the Federation
of Philippine Industries (EPI) to impose additional taxes on
foreign goods that are also produced locally, local press reported
Friday.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to President Ramos, EPI President Raul Concepcion
listed five whammies the country is facing, namely, depressed
consumer demand as people tighten their belt, contraction of
credit, tightening of money supply, cheap imports from countries
undergoing massive retrenchment, and continued operation of
duty-free shops.
</P>
<P>
Concepcion said the temporary additional tax is "necessary to
partially offset the huge projected fiscal deficit this year", and
that it will be a bleak year this year for the local manufacturers
who are suffering higher interest rates.
</P>
<P>
Based on the private sector projections, manufacturers will
have to dramatically cut down their production this year due to
lower consumer demand and increase in raw material imports.
</P>
<P>
Executive Secretary Ruben Torres said Concepcion's proposal
would be taken up in a special cabinet cluster meeting involving
monetary, fiscal and economic officials, together with the central
bank and business leaders shortly after New Year's day.
</P>
<P>
Since July last year, the peso has devaluated by some 52
percent to the current level of 40 pesos per U.S. dollar, causing
the interest rates to soar between 20 percent and 30 percent. The
Asian Development Bank and other multinational institutions have
urged the country to lower the interest rates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
