<HEADLINE> Highlights of Major Beijing-Based Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 2 (Xinhua) -- All the major Beijing-based
newspapers today front-paged the speech delivered by President
Jiang Zemin at a New Year tea party sponsored by the National
Committee of the Chinese People's Political Consultative
Conference yesterday,
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Jiang summarized the achievements made by the
country in pushing forward the reform, opening up and
modernization drive as well as in handling external relations in
the year 1997.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he urged the Taiwan authorities to put national
interests first and "respond at an early date to our serious call"
for negotiations across the Straits under the principle of "one
China."
</P>
<P>
"We will continue to stick to the basic policy of 'peaceful
reunification and one country, two systems,' and to the
eight-point proposal for developing relations across the Straits
and promoting the peaceful reunification of the motherland," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Other major stories in today's Beijing-based newspapers include:
</P>
<P>
-- The People's Daily reported that China opened its embassy in
the Republic of South Africa yesterday, as the two countries
established diplomatic relations.
</P>
<P>
-- The People's Daily carried an article by Wang Daohan,
President of the Association for Relations Across the Taiwan
Straits. Extending the new year's greetings to the Taiwan
Compatriots and all the people in support of the reunification
cause of the motherland, Wang expressed his wishes that relations
across the Taiwan Straits may enter a new period in 1998.
</P>
<P>
-- The China Daily reported that the bulk of the industrial
pollution sources along the Huaihe River have reached state
standards for the treatment of waste water before discharge.
</P>
<P>
-- The China Daily reported that state councillor Luo Gan
announced the beginning of the China City and Country Tour '98 in
Suzhou yesterday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
