<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, January 2 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING -- In China's sprawling territory, people celebrated
New Year's Day in merry and diverse ways.
</P>
<P>
On early Thursday morning in Beijing, capital of China, more
than 40,000 people from all walks of life braved a chilly winter
breeze to watch the hoisting of the national flag at Tian'anmen
Square while listening to the national anthem.
</P>
<P>
Major streets in Beijing were lined with national flags and
colorful banners. Large lantern-like balloons floated in the
air. Parks, stores and entertainment places were filled with
people greeting a new festival. (China-New Year Celebrations)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SEOUL -- South Korea's President-elect Kim Dae-jung on Thursday
called for national unity to overcome the current economic crisis
ailing the country.
</P>
<P>
"We are facing our biggest crisis since the Korean War. We
should unite to overcome the difficulties," Kim said in his New
Year's message to South Koreans.
</P>
<P>
Kim, who won the 15th presidential election on December 19,
said he will take the lead in pain sharing while the pain should
be born evenly and fairly by all South Koreans. (South Korea-Kim)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NAIROBI -- Hutu rebels in Burundi on Wednesday night massacred
over 100 civilians near the capital of Bujumbura in retaliation
for the killing of their 30 companions by the Burundi army, Rwanda
News Agency reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted the Burundi army spokesman Mames Sinarinzi as
saying that a very important group of armed Hutu rebels attempted
to storm a military barracks near the capital's airport on
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
They were repulsed by the army that killed 30 of the
assailants, who then crossed the airport causing some minor
damages to the airport's vehicles and buildings, he
added. (Burundi-Massacre)
</P>
<P>
