<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic News Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, January 1 (Xinhua) -- The following are the major
economic news briefs from Latin American countries over the past
few days:
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Brazil's pork production fell 2.7 percent to
475,000 tons in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The number of hogs slaughtered in 1997 was 6.4 million, a 4.5
percent drop against that of 1996 and pork was the only meat that
registered an output drop in 1997.
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- Chile's Yuletide season sales increased eight
percent in 1997, compared to one percent of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The 1997 sales increase is estimated at between three and four
percent, according to the Retail Commerce Confederation.
</P>
<P>
The Asian crisis could cause a downward revision of the
estimates for next year, it said.
</P>
<P>
SAN JOSE -- Costa Rican banana exports dropped 8.94 percent to
489.05 million U.S. dollars during the first 11 months of 1997,
the Foreign Trade Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
Costa Rica is the world's second biggest banana exporter and
producer. In 1996, it exported more than 106 million boxes worth
581 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- Supermarkets sales increased 7.9 percent in Chile
last November, the National Statistics Institute said.
</P>
<P>
The general index of supermarkets sales registered an 8.7
percent increase over the same period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- Uruguay's inflation rate reduced by 10 percent to
13.3 percent in 1997 and the index of prices to the consumer
showed its lowest level in December. 
</P>
</TEXT>
